<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06258124 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06258124 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  HOUSING; CLEANUP; GUIDELINE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  ONE of the simplest and most effective ways to extend the life of a carpet canbe explained easily: Vacuum, vacuum, vacuum.;   Don't worry about wearing downcarpet fibers by vacuuming too much. People are far more likely to damagetheir carpet by allowing dirt to become embedded in the fibers than byover-vacuuming.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Home  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  VACUUM TO PREVENT SUCKING LIFE FROM CARPETEMBEDDED DIRT CAN WEAR OUT RUGS FASTER  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Consumer  </MEMO><TEXT>     (check) Lightly vacuum heavy traffic areas daily (three passes of themachine over the same area). Vacuum the entire carpet thoroughly every week,running the vacuum over the same area six to seven times.;   (check) Spotprevention begins at the front door, where a floor mat can trap dirt.;  (check) Use shades, drapes, or blinds in sunny areas to protect the carpetfrom fading.;   (check) Blot spills immediately with a towel or tissue. Forspot-cleaning, mix water with a small amount of neutral detergent and applythe solution with a clean, white cloth. Excessive wetting may damage carpetbacking.;   (check) Have the carpet cleaned by professional hot-waterextraction. People shouldn't shampoo the rugs themselves. Shampooing can leavea soap residue on a carpet, which mats the fibers and attracts soil.;   Checka book; Planning to install carpet? The Carpet and Rug Institute's latestpublication, &quot;Steps in the Right Direction, an Owner's Manual for YourCarpet,&quot; covers installation, carpet characteristics, spots and spills,long-term care and environmental considerations.;   The manual is availablefor $1.25 from the Carpet and Rug Institute, P.O. Box 2048, Dalton, Ga.30722-2048; (404) 278-3176.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><P